SIMPLE: adventitious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: adventitious
<hw>ad`ven*ti"tious</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧d`v⟦ecr⟧n*t⟦icr⟧sh"⟦ucr⟧s)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>adventitius</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Added extrinsically; not essentially inherent.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> accidental; casual; incidental; additional;
supervenient; foreign.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>To things of great dimensions, if we annex an
<qex>adventitious</qex> idea of terror, they become without comparison
greater.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Nat. Hist.)</fld> <def>Out of the proper or usual
place; <as>as, <ex>adventitious</ex> buds or roots</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Accidentally or sparingly
spontaneous in a country or district; not fully naturalized; adventive;
-- applied to foreign plants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Acquired, as diseases; not
hereditary.</def> <au>AS</au> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Occurring in an unusual place or
arising from an external source.</def> <au>Stedman 25</au> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PC</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Ad`ven*ti"tious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Ad`ven*ti"tious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Adventive</ent>⟦br⟧
